Vision (one line)

A secure, interoperable, multilingual, offline-capable digital health platform that supports patients, community health workers, clinicians, labs, pharmacies and public-health authorities — with embedded AI for screening, triage, diagnostics support, and operational optimization.

1 — High-level modules (system map)

Patient-facing: mobile (Android/iOS), SMS/USSD fallback, multilingual, offline-first, consent & health education.

Clinician-facing: EMR/EHR web + mobile, clinical decision support (CDS), telemedicine, e-prescribing.

Community worker: lightweight app (ASHA/CHW) for surveys, screenings, offline sync, multimedia educational content.

Lab & Imaging integration: LIS, DICOM ingestion, structured lab results (LOINC).

Pharmacy & Supply chain: e-prescriptions, inventory, order/reorder alerts.

AI/ML Engine: model training & inference (screening, triage, outbreak detection, operational forecasting).

Public Health / Admin Dashboard: hotspots, dashboards, resource allocation, audit logs.

IoT & Sensors: vitals, water sensors, wearable telemetry ingestion.

Interoperability layer: FHIR / HL7 / OpenEHR adapters, API Gateway.

Security & Governance: auth, consent, encryption, audit, policies.

2 — Phased roadmap (recommended)
Phase 0 — Discovery & Compliance (2–4 weeks)

Stakeholder workshop (clinicians, CHWs, district health, patients).

Requirements: use-cases prioritized (screening, EHR, lab).

Legal review: data protection/regulatory (India: NDHM/ABHA/ABDM, clinical device laws; target export regs HIPAA/GDPR if needed).

Architecture & tech choices.
Deliverables: Product Requirements Doc (PRD), Compliance checklist, MVP feature list, initial wireframes.

Phase 1 — Core MVP (3–4 months)

Core EHR (patient profile, encounters, meds, lab results).

Patient + CHW apps (offline-first, multilingual).

Clinician web app + teleconsultation (audio/video).

Basic alerts & notification (SMS/WhatsApp).

Minimal AI: rule-based triage + one ML screening (e.g., speech dementia or fever/triage).

FHIR server + simple API gateway.
Success criteria: 3 clinics onboarded, 500 patient records, offline sync tested, basic AI screening integrated.

Phase 2 — Pilot & Integrations (3–6 months)

Integrate with local labs, pharmacy networks, and low-cost IoT sensors.

Add advanced ML pipelines (model registry, CI).

Dashboards for district health (hotspots, trends).

Consent / audit / role-based access hardened.
Success criteria: Pilot in one district, measurable KPIs (reduced time-to-treatment, detection rates).

Phase 3 — Validation & Scale (6–12 months)

Clinical validation studies for AI features (prospective).

Regulatory submissions if pursuing SaMD approval.

Scale infra (K8s, multi-region, autoscaling).

Training programs for users, operations manuals.
Success criteria: Clinical validation completed, regulatory milestones met, expansion plan.

Phase 4 — Continuous Ops & Expansion (ongoing)

Model monitoring & re-training.

Partner ecosystem (labs, insurance, ambulances).

Monetization & sustainability (govt contracts, grants, pay-per-use services).

3 — Prioritized MVP features (first 8, highest impact)

Patient registry + unique ID (linkable to ABHA/NDHM).

Encounter capture (SOAP notes), meds, allergies.

Offline mobile app for CHWs with sync.

Telemedicine (audio + basic video) + appointment scheduling.

Lab result ingestion (CSV/LIS integration).

Automated triage rules + one ML screening model.

SMS/WhatsApp alerts to clinicians and CHWs.

Admin dashboard: daily metrics, flagged cases list.

4 — Data model (core entities & sample fields)

Keep data normalized and use FHIR resources where possible.

Patient (core fields)

patient_id (UUID), national_id/ABHA, name, dob, sex, address (geo), primary_language, phone, consent_flags, created_at

Encounter

encounter_id, patient_id, datetime, facility_id, clinician_id, chief_complaint, notes (structured + free text), diagnosis_codes (ICD-10), vitals

Medications

med_id, encounter_id, drug_code (RxNorm/ATC), dose, frequency, route, duration, prescriber_id

LabResult

lab_id, encounter_id, test_code (LOINC), value, units, ref_range, specimen_datetime, result_status, attached_report (PDF)

IoTTelemetry

device_id, patient_id or location_id, metric_type, value, timestamp, device_status

Audit/Consent

audit_id, actor_id, action, resource, timestamp, ip, signed_consent_id

(Use FHIR Patient/Encounter/Observation/MedicationRequest/DiagnosticReport where possible.)

5 — Interoperability & standards

Primary standards: FHIR (R4), HL7 v2/v3 (legacy labs), DICOM (imaging), LOINC (labs), SNOMED/ICD (diagnosis), RxNorm/ATC (meds).

Implementation: HAPI-FHIR server or Google Cloud Healthcare API / Microsoft Azure API for FHIR. Provide FHIR façade for external integrations.

6 — AI/ML architecture & pipeline (stepwise)

Data ingestion: ETL -> anonymization -> feature store.

Labeling: clinician-verified labels (gold standard), active learning for edge cases.

Feature store: use Feast or a shared DB.

Models: start with explainable models (XGBoost/RandomForest) for triage; use deep models for complex tasks (speech, imaging).

MLOps: model registry (MLflow), CI/CD for models, automated testing, Canary or shadow deployments (Seldon/BentoML).

Inference: edge (mobile) for latency-sensitive screening; serverless/K8s inference for heavier models.

Monitoring: data drift, concept drift, performance metrics & explainability (SHAP/LIME).

Privacy: differential privacy / federated learning for sensitive cross-site models (if needed).

Tool suggestions: Python, scikit-learn, XGBoost, PyTorch/TensorFlow, MLflow, Kubeflow/Seldon, Feast, Airflow/Kedro.

7 — Security, privacy & compliance (must do)

Authentication & IAM: OAuth2 + OpenID Connect, RBAC, MFA for admins.

Encryption: TLS in transit; AES-256 at rest.

Consent & Access control: per-resource consent, granular sharing, emergency access auditing.

Audit logs: immutable logs (append-only), tamper evidence.

Data minimization: collect only necessary PII, pseudonymize for analytics.

Regulations: NDHM/ABHA compliance in India, HIPAA/GDPR for international users — engage legal early.

Pen testing: prelaunch pentest + periodic vulnerability scans.

8 — Offline & multilingual strategy

Offline-first apps: local SQLite/Realm, conflict resolution sync, resumable uploads.

Multilingual UX: externalize all strings, support vernacular fonts/Unicode, audio prompts, TTS/ASR for low literacy.

Low-bandwidth: compressed JSON, delta syncs, background sync, image optimization.

9 — IoT & sensor integration

Gateway model: LoRa/Edge device → gateway (Raspberry Pi) → MQTT broker → cloud ingestion.

Edge processing: validate, buffer, and batch upload.

Calibration & tamper detection: periodic calibration, device health telemetry.

Security: device auth, signed firmware updates.

10 — UX & workflows (role flows)

Patient flow: Register → consent → self-report/symptom diary → teleconsult → receive Rx/education.

CHW flow: daily household rounds → offline case entries → flag to clinician → follow up scheduling.

Clinician flow: inbox of flagged cases → review EHR + labs + AI score → teleconsult or refer → capture outcome.

Admin flow: dashboards, resource requests, outbreak alerts, export reports.

Design tips: large touch targets, clear icons, progressive disclosure, offline prompts, short micro-learning modules.

11 — Testing, validation & clinical trials

Technical tests: unit, integration, load, security.

Usability tests: in field with CHWs & patients (iterative).

Clinical validation: prospective study design, IRB approval, sample size for diagnostic accuracy (sensitivity/specificity), endpoints defined. Partner with local hospitals/universities.

A/B and QA: controlled rollouts and shadow deployments for ML features.

12 — Regulatory & ethics (short checklist)

Ethics board / IRB approvals for data collection.

Clinical validation plan for any AI used in decision support (SaMD).

Regulatory filings: consult with local regulatory body about Software as Medical Device rules.

Clear disclaimers, escalation/referral pathway, adverse-event reporting mechanism.

13 — Deployment & infra (suggested stack)

Cloud: AWS/Azure/GCP or hybrid (edge + cloud).

Containers: Docker + Kubernetes (EKS/GKE/AKS).

DB: PostgreSQL (primary), ElasticSearch (search), Redis (cache/queue).

Object storage: S3 (or-compatible).

CI/CD: GitHub Actions / GitLab CI.

Monitoring: Prometheus + Grafana, ELK stack for logs.

Mobile backend: FastAPI / Node.js, GraphQL optional.

14 — Team roles & org needs

Product Manager (healthcare experience)

Clinical lead (MD) + epidemiologist

Backend engineers (2–4)

Mobile engineers (2)

Frontend/dashboard (1–2)

DevOps / SRE (1–2)

ML engineers (1–2) + data engineer (1)

QA & security engineer (1)

Field ops / CHW trainers (2–4)

Legal / Compliance advisor (contract)

UX researcher + designer (1–2)

15 — KPIs & success metrics (examples)

Adoption: number of active CHWs / clinicians / patients.

Data quality: % of encounters with complete structured data.

Clinical impact: time-to-treatment, referral completion rate.

AI performance: sensitivity & specificity, AUC, calibration.

Operational: sync success rate, uptime, average response time.

Cost: cost per patient screened, sustainability metrics.

16 — Risks & mitigations

Data quality / bias → mitigation: strict data schema, clinician labeling, model stratified eval.

Low connectivity → offline-first design and async sync.

Regulatory hurdles → start compliance early, partner with hospitals.

Adoption resistance → heavy field training, incentivize CHWs, simple UI.

Security breaches → hardened infra, encryption, audits.

17 — Rough cost & timeline estimate (very high-level)

MVP (3–6 months): small core team — dev + product + clinical advisor ≈ $80k–$200k (depending on region & infra choices).

Pilot (6–12 months): integrations, field ops, devices ≈ $200k–$600k.

Scale (12–24 months): validation, regulatory, ops ≈ $500k–$2M+.
Costs vary hugely by personnel costs, hardware, cloud usage, and fieldwork.

